nnection: Lithuanian Music and the Warsaw Autumn Festival -- t14. Performing Polishness Abroad: (Non-)Polish Actors and the Construction of (Trans)National Identities in European Cinema -- t15. “Poles—Their Own Portraits” Revisited: Taking a Critical Stand -- tAfterword: Polishness: A Time of Deconstruction, a Time of Reconstruction -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA critical examination of the category of "Polishness" - that is, the formation, redefinition, and performance of various kinds of Polish identities - from a wide range of disciplinary perspectives.Inspired by new research in the humanities and social sciences as well as recent scholarship on national identities, this volume offers a rigorous examination of the idea of Polishness. Offering a diversity of case studies and methodological-theoretical approaches, it demonstrates a profound connection between national and transnational processes and places the Polish case in a broader context. This broader context stretches from a larger Eastern European one, a usual frame of comparison, to the overseas immigrant communities. The authors, renowned scholars from Europe and the United States, thus demonstrate that an understanding of modern Polish identity means crossing not only historical but also geographical boundaries.Consequently, the narrative on Polish identity that unfolds in the volume is a personalized and multivocal one that presents the perspectives of a wide range of subjects: peasants, workers, migrants, ethnic and sexual minorities-that is, all those actors who have been absent in grand national narratives. As such, the examination of Polishness sheds light on the identity question more broadly, emphasizing the interplay of pluralizing and homogenizing tendencies, and fostering a reflection on national identity as encompassing both sameness and difference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational characteristics, Polish. 0aNationalismxHistoryy20th centuryzPoland. 0aNationalismzPolandxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolish peoplexEthnic identity. 4aEast European Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Poland.2bisacsh  aEastern Europe.  aEthnic Minorities.  aHumanities.  aMigrants.  aNational Identity.  aPeasants.  aSexual Minorities.  aSocial Science.  aWorkers.1 aBukowiec, Paweł, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiancia, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzapliński, Przemysław, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalbraith, Marysia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabowska, Magdalena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrudzinska-Gross, Irena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrudzińska-Gross, Irena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeuckelom, Kris Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIllakowicz, Krystyna Lipińska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJakelski, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoziołek, Ryszard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipińska Illakowicz, Krystyna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLitwinowicz, Małgorzata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasieka, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasieka, Agnieszka, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPorter-Szűcs, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g